                <head>93. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The 14th regular session of the <gloss target="#t_UN1">U.N</gloss>. General
                    Assembly opened at 3 p.m., September 15. <persName corresp="#p_BVA1">Victor A.
                        Belaunde</persName> of Peru was elected President of the session. For a
                    record of these proceedings, see U.N. doc. <gloss target="#t_A1"
                    >A</gloss>/PV.795.</p>
                <p>Secretary of State Herter addressed the General Assembly during general debate on
                    September 17. Herter spoke of several foreign policy issues in terms of the
                    theme “constructive change through peaceful <pb facs="0209" n="179"
                        xml:id="pg_179"/> means.” For text of his statement, see <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">U.N</gloss>. doc. <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>/PV.797.
                    Three days later, the American Broadcast Company televised a statement by Herter
                    about the United Nations, in which he termed it “a cornerstone of United States
                    foreign policy.” For text, see Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                        >Bulletin,</hi> October 12, 1959, pages 507–508.</p>
            </div>
